*. (First published in 1960 by Cassel, London.)
* Original hardback edition published by Weidenfeld &amp; Nicolson (London), 2002. Published in New York by H. Holt.
*. Modern annotated translation in pp. 19–50.
*. Modernised text in pp. 225–238
*. A brief summary of this book (in English) appears in Newsletter 44, p.24 of the Brussels Map Circle. There is also a review in Newsletter 45, p.7.
*
*. EMS Newsletter March 2016, p44.
*. The latin text is included was printed in the 1595 atlas which may be viewed at websites such as the Library of Congress or the Darlington Library at the University of Pittsburgh. For translations see pages 185–194 and pages 7–24 of the atlas text, pdf pages 77–94.
*. Published on the occasion of an exhibition at the Plantin-Moretus Museum.
*. (Pages 155–166 of &quot;Théorie et pratique de l&#x27;exégèse. Actes du 3me colloque international sur l&#x27;histoire de l&#x27;exégèse biblique au XVIme siècle&quot;, Geneva, Droz, 1990).
*. This commentary, which accompanies the facsimile edition of the 1595 atlas published by Octavo (), is freely available in an archived version. from the New York Society Library, pages 1–20 of the introduction to the atlas (pdf pages 2–21). 
*. The six volumes of this work are available from the Mercator pages of Krücken&#x27;s web site().
*
*. See also the web site of the Galileo Museum globes
*This website is a digital resource for teachers of history in the Netherlands. The article is in Dutch but there is a link to an English version. ().
*. Chapter 3, Mercator&#x27;s Résumé, has been made available (with permission) at Roma Tre University. 
*. Osley&#x27;s translation is pages 185–194. For another translation of &#x27;Vita Mercatoris&#x27; see pages 7–24 of the atlas text, pdf pages 77–94.
*. This is a catalogue prepared for an exhibition at the Mercator Museum in Sint-Niklaas, 1994. It includes over 100 illustrations of title pages of books known to be in Mercator&#x27;s library (but not his own copies).
*
*. This translation, which accompanies the facsimile edition of the 1595 atlas published by Octavo (), is freely available in an archived version from the New York Society Library. 
*. A facsimile of this book is available at Archive.org and a modern (clearer) transcription is available at Scientificlib.com
*. A summary of this book is available online .
*. Reissued in facsimile by Adamant Media Corporation (). It is also freely available at the Hathi Trust and Google books.
*. Reissued in facsimile by Adamant Media Corporation (). It is also freely available at Google books.
*. Includes 17 facsimile maps and an introduction and 4 other articles: The atlas of Europe (Marcel Watelet), Atlas, birth of a title (James R. Akerman), The map of Europe (Arthur Dürst, The British Isles (Peter M. Barber), The 1569 world map (Mireille Pastoureau). Abstracts. A substantial excerpt of Barber&#x27;s article appeared in the Mercator&#x27;s World magazine.
*. Chapter 6 on &quot;Globes in Renaissance Europe&quot; by Dekker is available online. Chapter 44 on &quot;Commercial Cartography and Map Production in the Low Countries, 1500–ca. 1672&quot; by Cornelis Koeman, Günter Schilder, Marco van Egmond, and Peter van der Krogt is also available online. 
